    "prompt": "<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents two particle diagrams of electrochemical cells. Each diagram includes a container holding molten N a C l, a submerged anode and a cathode, and a wire connected to a voltage source that has a switch. &nbsp;In the container on the left, with an open switch, there are ten C l with a negative one charge particles and ten N a with a positive one charge particles, randomly arranged. In the container on the right, with the closed switch, there are six C l with a negative one charge particles and six N a with a positive one charge particles, randomly arranged. There are two Cl 2 particles on the anode and 4 Na particles on the cathode.\" height=\"407\" src=\"/images/ff267de0ca899f2cab10eb6b5ec2f2bc.png\" width=\"700\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The particle diagrams above represent <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"N a C l liquid\"><math alttext=\"N a C l liquid\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>NaCl</mtext><mo>(</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and its decomposition into <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"N a liquid\"><math alttext=\"N a liquid\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>Na</mtext><mo>(</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C l 2 gas\"><math alttext=\"C l 2 gas\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mtext>Cl</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>(</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> in an electrochemical cell after voltage is applied. Which of the following statements about the thermodynamic favorability of the decomposition of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"N a C l liquid\"><math alttext=\"N a C l liquid\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>NaCl</mtext><mo>(</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is supported by the particle diagrams and why?</p>\n",
